06216nam a22010935i 9780691200828DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912008287 a10.1515/97806912008282doi  a(DE-B1597)548907  a(OCoLC)1192382033  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDG233.2 7aHIS0020202bisacsh04a937.022231 aPadilla Peralta, Dan-el, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivine Institutions :bReligions and Community in the Middle Roman Republic /cDan-el Padilla Peralta. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b9 color illus. 12 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tFigures, Color Plates, and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction: One State, under the Gods -- tPart I Build -- t2 Temple Construction: From Vows to Numbers -- t3 Temples and the Civic Order: From Numbers to Rhythms -- tPart II Socialize -- t4 Temples, Festivals, and Common Knowledge: From Rhythms to Identities -- t5 Pilgrimage to Mid-Republican Rome: From Dedications to Social Networks -- t6 Conclusion: Religion and the Enduring State -- tAppendix: The Pocola Deorum: An Annotated Catalog -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow religious ritual united a growing and diversifying Roman RepublicMany narrative histories of Rome's transformation from an Italian city-state to a Mediterranean superpower focus on political and military conflicts as the primary agents of social change. Divine Institutions places religion at the heart of this transformation, showing how religious ritual and observance held the Roman Republic together during the fourth and third centuries BCE, a period when the Roman state significantly expanded and diversified.Blending the latest advances in archaeology with innovative sociological and anthropological methods, Dan-el Padilla Peralta takes readers from the capitulation of Rome's neighbor and adversary Veii in 398 to the end of the Second Punic War in 202, demonstrating how the Roman state was redefined through the twin pillars of temple construction and pilgrimage. He sheds light on how the proliferation of temples together with changes to Rome's calendar created new civic rhythms of festival celebration, and how pilgrimage to the city surged with the increase in the number and frequency of festivals attached to Rome's temple structures.Divine Institutions overcomes many of the evidentiary hurdles that for so long have impeded research into this pivotal period in Rome's history. This book reconstructs the scale and social costs of these religious practices and reveals how religious observance emerged as an indispensable strategy for bringing Romans of many different backgrounds to the center, both physically and symbolically.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPilgrims and pilgrimageszRome. 0aTempleszRome. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh  aAventine.  aBuilding Mid-Republican Rome.  aCampus Martius.  aCapitoline Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus.  aCapitoline Temple.  aCarthage.  aForum Boarium.  aForum Romanum.  aHannibal.  aHannibalic War.  aJohn North.  aLivy.  aMary Beard.  aNathan Rosenstein.  aReligions of Rome.  aRoman Forum.  aRoman religion.  aRoman temples.  aRome at War.  aSanctuary of Ceres, Liber, and Libera.  aScipio Africanus.  aSeth Bernard.  aSimon Price.  aTemple of Apollo Medicus.  aTemple of Castor and Pollux.  aTemple of Fortuna.  aTemple of Portunus.  aTiberius.  aTitus Livius.  aancient Rome.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBO